\f0\fs24 \cf0 The families who attended were notable and prominent in London politics and business, science and commerce. Aristocrats, foreign dignitaries, ministers, and scientists. The well-to-do. The sort of ladies whose choices of garments would make the morning Post. The sort of men who earned more in an hour than most men earn in a year and for whom the idea of hard labor is as terrifying as the bubonic plague.
\f1\fs20 \

\f0\fs24 The receipt of an invitation to the masquerade was widely considered to be a compliment of the highest regard. Young ladies would wait with increasing suspense to see that cream-colored envelope enclosed with Connor\'92s seal, and failing to receive one, would be understandably brought to the brink of despair.
\f1\fs20 \
