{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://A0C64526-E3B5-46C4-B472-1308C5976BB4"}}{\fldrslt \cf0 Annabel Grey\cb3  was perhaps the exception to that rule. She\cb1  had neither received an invitation to Lord Connor\'92s ball, nor had she barricaded herself in her room in a fit of tears.}} Of course, Annabel was not exactly a lady, per se. Just a common woman, who had worked her way into the upper echelons through hard work, perseverance, raw talent, and most importantly\'97cheating. 
\f1\fs20 \

\f0\fs24 Even her identity was stolen. Her adopted name, Miss Monday, for example. \'a0The real Miss Monday had died in a tragic house fire, along with the rest of her family. It had been simple enough for Annabel Grey to assume Lady Monday\'92s identity by retrieving the paperwork concerning her death. The unfortunate young woman had no surviving family members to dispute Annabel\'92s claim, and Annabel had friends who specialized in insurance fraud. Annabel had dozens of identities\'97earned in a similar manner\'97but 
\i Miss Monday
\i0  was a particular favorite. As Miss Monday, Annabel had claimed not only the insurance money, but also a sizable inheritance from her parents, who had both died in the fire.
\f1\fs20 \

\f0\fs24 Still, Annabel had not anticipated an invitation to Lord Connor\'92s. In fact, she\'92d had no plans to attend the party\'97notn.
\f1\fs20 \

\f0\fs24 Not until recently, anyway. Now, her circumstances had changed. Now she 
\i had
\i0  to get into the ball; \cb3 . Not only that,\cb1  she needed to seek an audience with Lord Connor himself. As for the lack of an invitation, that was hardly enough to deter her.
